@bexhill8777 Chernobyl was a uniquely bad incident. The Chernobyl power plant was poorly built and poorly run. The exact same fault that occurred in the Chernobyl reactor also occured in 3-Mile-Island but because that reactor was well built and well run, the meltdown was contained and no one died as a result.

The accident at the Fukushima Daiichi plant only occurred after it was hit with an earthquake and 2 tsunamis in quick succession. Again the leak was contained and no one died. Much of the Fukushima exclusion zone has even been repopulated because the radiation levels are well within safe limits.

The general safety of different methods of electricity production is measured in deaths per TWh. Using this metric we can see that natural gas is the safest fossil fuel, resulting in 2.82 deaths per TWh. Nuclear results in 0.03 deaths per TWh, 94x safer than natural gas and an astonishing 821x safer than coal. The only form of electricity production safer than nuclear is solar power with 0.02 deaths per TWh compared to nuclear's 0.03 but we're really splitting hairs at that point.
